The Philadelphia Flyers are a professional ice hockey team based in
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. They are members of the Metropolitan Division of the
National Hockey League's (NHL) Eastern Conference. The Flyers were founded in
1967 as one of six expansion teams, increasing the size of the NHL at that time
to 12 teams.

Since the franchise was established, the team has had 19 captains,
including Bobby Clarke, who captained the Flyers to two Stanley Cups in 1973â74
and 1974â75, and is the only player to have scored over 1,000 points for the
Flyers. Clarke was awarded the Hart Trophy as the NHL's most valuable
player three times, and was inducted into the Hockey Hall of Fame in
1987. Eight other players who have appeared for the Flyers have been
inducted into the Hockey Hall of Fame: Bill Barber, Paul Coffey, Dale Hawerchuk,
Mark Howe, Adam Oates, Bernie Parent, Darryl Sittler and Allan
Stanley. Five players have been honored by having their number
retired by the Flyers: Barber, Clarke, Howe, Parent and Barry Ashbee. {{cite
web|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=435619 |title=Flyers Heroes of
the Past: Barry Ashbee |publisher=Philadelphia Flyers |accessdate=2010-03-
28}} Twenty people have been inducted into the Flyers Hall of Fame since
its establishment in 1988, of which fifteen have been players.

In addition to leading the team in points both in the regular season and
playoffs, Clarke also holds the records for the most appearances and most
assists for the Flyers in both regular season and playoffs. Fellow Stanley Cup
winner Barber has scored the most goals for the team with his 420 regular season
and 53 playoff goals. Rick Tocchet spent the most time in the penalty box during
the regular season for the Flyers, accruing 1,817 minutes in total, while Dave
Schultz's 363 penalty minutes are the most by a Flyer in the playoffs. Among
goaltenders, Roman Cechmanek boasts the best goals against average and save
percentage in the regular season (excluding Marc D'Amour and Robbie Moore,
neither of whom made more than five appearances).

As of April 27, 2013, 49 goaltenders and 513 skaters (forwards and defensemen)
have appeared in at least one regular season and/or playoff game with the
Philadelphia Flyers since the team joined the league in the 1967â68 NHL
season. The figure of 513 skaters includes 11 debutants in
addition to the 502 listed at hockeydb.com, and the figure of 49 goaltenders
includes 1 debutant in addition to the 48 listed at hockeydb.com. The
Flyers won the Stanley Cup in 1974 and 1975 with a total of 26
players. Seventeen of them were part of both Stanley Cup
